7. Findings (With Evidence)
User Actions Summary
Action	Count	Percentage
Email Opened	27	90%
Link Clicked	18	60%
Credentials Submitted	7	23%
Reported Email	4	13%
Findings

Majority of users clicked without verifying the sender.

Some users entered credentials on a suspicious page.

Few users reported the phishing attempt to IT security.

Lack of awareness regarding checking URL legitimacy.

8. Mitigation Strategies

Conduct mandatory phishing awareness training.

Implement multi-factor authentication to reduce credential compromise.

Regularly update users about new phishing campaigns.

Enable email filtering and anti-phishing gateways.

Add banners to external emails (“This email originated outside the organization”).

9. Incident Response Simulation
9.1 Attack Detection in Logs

Identified suspicious login attempts from phishing landing page logs.

Detected anomalous IP address submissions.

[Screenshot Placeholder: Logs Evidence]

9.2 Containment Actions

Reset passwords of affected users.

Blocked suspicious IPs in the firewall.

Disabled compromised accounts temporarily.

Forced organization-wide password reset (if needed).

9.3 Eradication & Recovery

Removed phishing landing page.

Ensured no persistent threats.

Reconfigured filters to block similar phishing emails.

9.4 Post-Incident Report

The phishing simulation exposed several user awareness gaps. With proper training and preventive security measures, the organization can significantly reduce phishing risks. The incident response process helped ensure compromised accounts were secured and malicious access was prevented.

10. Conclusion

The Security Awareness Phishing Simulation successfully measured user awareness levels, identified weaknesses, and demonstrated the importance of cybersecurity training. The project emphasizes continuous improvement, awareness sessions, and technical defenses to combat phishing threats.

End of Report
